## Software Installation & Setup
Getting Shortcuit running is incredibly simple. Because it uses KMK and CircuitPython, there is absolutely zero C-code compiling required. You just drag, drop, and edit text files!

Here is how to get your board up and running from scratch:

### Step 1: Flash CircuitPython
1. Download the latest CircuitPython '.uf2' file specifically for the **Raspberry Pi Pico W** from the [offical CircuitPython website](https://circuitpython.org/board/raspberry_pi_pico_w).
2. Hold down the physical **BOOTSEL** button on the Pico W (the tiny white button) and plug it into your computer via USB.
3. A new flash drive called 'RPI-RP2' will appear on your computer.
4. Drag and drop the downloaded '.uf2' file onto that drive. the pico will automatically intall it, reboot, and reappear as a new drive named 'CIRCUITPY'.

### step 2: Upload the Shortcuit Code
1. Clone or download **Shortcuit Firmware** (click the download button at the top of the page and select "download Zip", then extract it).
2. Copy the entire contents of the firmware folder which include 'KMK' folder, 'kb.py', 'main.py', and 'boot.py' and paste them directly into the root of your 'CIRCUITPY' drive.
> *Safety Note* If you copy the 'boot.py' file over, it tell your computer to recognize the device as "SHORTCUIT" and hide the internal storage for a cleaner feel. Once you use it, the drive will be hidden. To see your files again, just hold down the top-left key (SW1) while plugging the macro pad into your computer!

Your final 'CIRCUITPY' drive should look exactly like this:
├── kmk/
├── boot.py
├── kb.py
└── main,py
### Customizing Your Keys
want to map a new shortcuit from a game or design app? you don't need special software
Just open 'main.py' in Notepad or VS Code, chanfw the keycodes, press save. the Pico W will reboot instantly with your new layout applied.
